The UV–vis absorption spectrum (Fig. S2) showed obvious absorption at 275 nm together with broad-band absorption in range of 300–700 nm, which was attributed to the π-π* and n-π* transitions of certain fluorophores [58]. The powdered SSF-CDs displayed a bright-light yellow fluorescence (Fig. 2
                     a inset) upon UV irradiation. Specifically, powdered SSF-CDs exhibited excitation-dependent emission (Fig. 2a and Fig. S3). The PL excitation (PLE) spectrum recorded by monitoring the PL peak at 510 nm showed a maximum at 440 nm, in good agreement with the PL spectrum (Fig. S4), and the CIE chromaticity coordinates of (0.3117, 0.5019) (Fig. 2b). The fluorescence quantum yield of the SSF-CDs was 10% and the fluorescence emission best fitted a double-exponential decay model, with an average lifetime of 3.99 ns (Fig. 2c). Importantly, since the preparation requires no cumbersome separation and purification steps, the yield of SSF-CDs can reach ~100%. To our knowledge, this is higher than the yield of previously described solid-state CDs (Table 1
                     ) [13,59–61]. The simple preparation and high yield mean that SSF-CDs can easily be produced on a large scale, at low cost. The bright light-yellow fluorescence of the SSF-CDs can be mixed with blue light to produce white light, demonstrating the practical applications of the SSF-CDs.
